Anonymous Fri 23 Feb 2024 21:54:28 No.63520323 Report
Quoted By: >>63520684
>>63519930
If you want exposition to feel natural, it will need to be through dialogue. Of course, in the first few paragraphs you'll need to set the stage, but I wouldn't go over 800 words of introduction before the characters begin to act. (That's not a hard limit, that's just a suggestion)
World info can be given through a lot of ways. Since your MC is new to the region, locals can explain things to him. Not in long winded ways of course, but it could look something like
>Bob the human walked through the town, and saw a horse drawn carriage barrel past him, nearly knocking him over. He had seen horses all the time back home, but he had heard that they weren't native to this region.
>"That's odd." He said to Jane the anthro. "I thought horses were rare here, but I see them at every building, not to mention that carriage."
>Jane the anthro looked at him sideways. "Horses have been here for decades! Your Spanish people brought them ages ago, and no one can get enough. Does the news of the frontier not travel back where you come from?"
>"Not really." Replied bob. "There's all sorts of things that don't make sense."

And back and forth, so on and so forth, yadda yadda yadda. Maybe he doesn't ask a character, but just a towns person who gives him a quick detail before walking away. Or, and this is important to do, have certain details unexplained. Have the main character remark on a detail, and how he doesn't understand it, and then move on. Do that a hundred times over a few chapters, interjecting action and characterization, and your exposition should go down easy.

Anonymous Fri 23 Feb 2024 23:03:02 No.63521866 Report
Quoted By: >>63522356 >>63522407 >>63523371
>>63521384
Don't sweat it man. I had never written romance before my last story either. Some advice I was given that is pretty sound regarding relationships is that they work best if the characters behave the same way in the relationship, as our of the relationship. In other words, if the characters change the way they talk before and after falling in love, then it won't feel natural. Chemistry between characters works best when they live each other for how they usually are, so if the stoic character suddenly only talks lovey dovey, it will come off as janky. Trust building romance is a really fun way to write that.
